# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arabian-oryx-reintroduction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] US$5 billion in funding for a project called the "Protecting Our Planet Challenge" was announced for the initiative in September 2021.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] In December 2022, 30 by 30 was agreed at the COP15 meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity, and became a target of the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] This includes the G7 and European Union.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] The initiative has attracted controversy over indigenous rights issues.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] As of May 2026, 17.3% of terrestrial land and inland waters and 9.8% of marine areas are protected.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] Including OECM's (Other Effective Area-based Conservation Measures) the percent of protected areas are 18.4% of terrestrial and inland waters and 10.0% of marine areas.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] The European Commission's Biodiversity strategy for 2030 was proposed on May 20, 2020, as the European Union's contribution to a post-2020 global biodiversity framework.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] The plan includes turning 30% of EU territory to protected area by 2030 and 10% to strictly protected area.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] However as of 2023 EU is not on track to meet the targets.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] The biodiversity strategy is a core part of the European Green Deal, and also intended to support green recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] In July 2023 after many debates the European parliament adopted a version of the Nature restoration law, aiming to restore nature on 20% of the territory of the European Union by 2030.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] In 2024, the European Union passed a nature restoration law aiming to restore 20% of degraded ecosystems by 2030 and 100% by 2050.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] On January 27, 2021, President Joe Biden issued an executive order on "Tackling the Climate Crisis at Home and Abroad".
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] Participating federal agencies included the U.S.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] Department of Commerce, and Council on Environmental Quality.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] The order also established a California Biodiversity Collaborative composed of representatives of government agencies, Native tribes, experts, and other stakeholders.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] The official report, *Pathways to 30x30 California*, was issued by the California Natural Resources Agency on 22 April 2022.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has progressed unevenly, and researchers caution that simply increasing the extent of protected areas is not sufficient to halt biodiversity loss.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] Some conservationists argue that the 30% figure lacks a clear scientific justification and risks being treated as a symbolic or political benchmark rather than a threshold grounded in ecological evidence.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] At the same time, other researchers and advocacy groups contend that 30% may in fact be too low to secure long‑term ecological integrity, and point to proposals such as the "Half‑Earth" concept, which calls for roughly 50% of terrestrial and marine realms to be conserved in some form.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] A further concern relates to the quality and effectiveness of protection once areas are designated.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] Researchers and NGOs have highlighted the persistence of so‑called "paper parks": protected areas that exist in law but lack adequate funding, staffing or enforcement, allowing activities such as poaching, illegal logging, or unregulated development to continue.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] Modelling work by Kuempel et al. suggests that, for exploited species, improving enforcement and management within existing protected areas can in many cases deliver greater conservation benefits than simply expanding the network’s total area without a corresponding increase in resources.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] Taken together, this literature underlines that meeting percentage‑based targets without adequate governance capacity risks diluting scarce conservation resources.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] Other research has examined conditions under which expanding protected areas can still be beneficial even when management budgets do not increase.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] Their results suggest that, in landscapes where human pressures are spatially clumped near reserve boundaries, strategically increasing the size of protected areas can create more secure habitat refuges even without proportional increases in staffing or enforcement.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] In practice, the 30 by 30 commitment has also prompted debate over how "protected" or "conserved" areas are defined for monitoring and reporting purposes.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has also raised concerns about “green grabbing” and green colonialism in the way new protected and conserved areas may be established.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] Similar critiques have been echoed by human rights organisations and researchers who argue that percentage-based conservation targets can replicate earlier "fortress conservation" models if they are implemented through top-down land designations that disregard customary tenure and existing uses.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] More broadly, some Indigenous organisations have criticised the way 30 by 30 has been promoted and negotiated, arguing that it risks appropriating Indigenous lands under the guise of biodiversity conservation.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] The COP15 included 196 parties in negotiations, with competing views regarding the adoption of the 30 by 30 target being wide-spread and well documented.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] The resulting agreement of the conference, the Convention on Biological Diversity, was signed by every party, with the exception of two: the United States and the Vatican.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] Towards the end of the talks, a negotiator from Democratic Republic of the Congo raised objections to the agreement, citing a lack of funding separate from the current Global Environment Facility (GEF).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] After a delay, COP15 president and Chinese environment minister Huang Runqiu overruled the objection due to a legal technicality, resulting in the passage of the agreement.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] Delegates from the DRC, Cameroon, and Uganda were reportedly displeased with the outcome.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/30-by-30] After the agreement was passed, the DRC's government announced that it would not recognize it as valid.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In 2026 Aden had a population estimated at 1,194,160, making it one of the largest cities in Yemen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] It is the capital and principal part of Aden Governorate, encompassing eight districts.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] During the colonial period, the name *Aden* referred to the area along the north coast of the gulf, encompassing Tawahi, Mualla, Crater, and much of Khor Maksar district.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The western harbour peninsula, known as *Little Aden*, now falls within the Al Buraiqeh district.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The city and surrounding area were under British administration from 1839 until independence in 1967.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Before gaining independence, Aden comprised distinct sectors: Crater, the original port; Ma'alla, the modern port; Tawahi, formerly "Steamer Point"; and Gold Mohur resorts.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Khormaksar, on the isthmus connecting Aden to the mainland, hosts diplomatic missions, Aden University's main offices, and Aden International Airport.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Aden encloses the eastern side of a vast natural harbour that constitutes the modern port.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Little Aden was developed as the site of the oil refinery and tanker port.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Both were established and operated by British Petroleum until they were turned over to South Yemeni government ownership and control in 1978.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Aden used to be the capital of South Yemen until its union with North Yemen on 22 May 1990.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] It has been the temporary capital of Yemen since the start of the Yemeni civil war, hosting some members of the Cabinet of Yemen mainly in al-Maashiq Palace.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] It was also the seat of the secessionist Southern Transitional Council from 2018 to 2026.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Aden is a home and a place for ships, and in Arabic the word "Aden" means residence, and it is said "Aden Al-Balad", meaning the settlement of the country.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Yaqut al-Hamwi said: "It is a famous city on the coast of the Indian Sea, towards the Yemen, and it is poor, with no water or pasture.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Ibn Khaldun said: "This Aden is one of the most fortified cities in Yemen, and it is on the bank of the Indian Sea.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Aden is an ancient port and was mentioned by the Greeks under the name (Ancient Greek: Αραβία Εμπόριον, romanised: *Arabia Emporion*), which means an Arabic trade port.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The port's convenient position on the sea route between India and Europe has made Aden desirable to rulers who sought to possess it at various times throughout history.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The same work describes Aden as "a village by the shore", which would well describe the town of Crater while it was still little developed.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] There is no mention of fortification at this stage.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Aden was more an island than a peninsula, as the isthmus (a tombolo) was not then so developed as it is today.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] At its beginning, the city was a small peninsula with no significant natural resources, but its location between Egypt and India made it important in the ancient Indian Ocean trade route.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The city was the home of the ancient Kingdom of Awsan from the eighth to seventh centuries BC.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In the second half of the first century BC, the Roman Emperor Augustus Caesar determined to control Arabia Felix and reach the Indian Ocean.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Aelius Gallus' Roman expedition to Arabia Felix (26–25 BCE) aimed to capture the Sabaean capital of Marib but failed due to extreme desert conditions, disease, and logistical challenges.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] After an unsuccessful week-long siege, the army, weakened by illness and dehydration, withdrew, losing most of its ~10,000 troops to environmental factors and disease" The Himyarites overthrew the Kingdom of Sheba in 275 AD and took control of Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Recent incomplete archaeological studies suggest that the Himyarites were the ones who built the huge water cisterns currently known as the "Cisterns of Aden", which stored approximately 136,382,757 litres of water.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Himyarite Kingdom fell in the first quarter of the sixth century AD.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Yusuf Dhu Nuwas mentioned Bab al-Mandab in one of his writings.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The forces of the Kingdom of Aksum were entering Yemen through it.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Byzantine Emperor Justinian I sent a fleet to fight the Himyarite Jews and support the Kingdom of Aksum and the Christians of Najran.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Byzantine sources indicate that the Sasanian Empire took control of the city in 571 AD.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] A local legend in Yemen states that Aden may be as old as human history itself.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Some also believe that Cain and Abel are buried somewhere in the city.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Although the pre-Islamic Himyar civilisation was capable of building large structures, there seems to have been little fortification at this stage.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Fortifications at Mareb and other places in Yemen and the Hadhramaut make it clear that both the Himyar and the Sabean cultures were well capable of it.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Thus, watchtowers, since destroyed, are possible.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] However, the Arab historians Ibn al Mujawir and Abu Makhramah attribute the first fortification of Aden to Beni Zuree'a.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Abu Makhramah has also included a detailed biography of Muhammad Azim Sultan Qamarbandi Naqsh in his work, Tarikh ul-Yemen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The aim seems to have been twofold: to keep hostile forces out and to maintain revenue by controlling the movement of goods, thereby preventing smuggling.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In its original form, some of this work was relatively feeble.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] With the introduction of Islam to Yemen in the seventh century AD, Aden experienced a period of stagnation that lasted until the ninth century AD.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In the early years of Islam, Aden belonged to the province of Jund (Taiz).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] It was controlled by the state of Ziyadid and the Sulayhid.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] After the death of Ali bin Muhammad Al-Sulayhi, his son took charge of Zurayids, and Aden continued to pay the annual royalty until Queen Arwa bint Ahmed Al-Sulayhi reduced it.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] After the fall of the Sulayhid state, the Banu Zurayi became independent in Aden, taking advantage of the Sulayhids' preoccupation with the Khawlan tribes.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Zurayites continued to rule Aden, Lahj, and Abyan for less than forty years until they fell under the Ayyubids' control of the city.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] A major battle took place between Turan Shah bin Ayyub and Yasser bin Bilal al-Muhammadi, Minister of State, and the Zurayiyyah were defeated and al-Muhammadi fled to Taiz.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] One of the most important contributors to the defeat of the Zurayids was their ongoing wars with the Bani Mahdi in Tihama and the departure of their army to confront the Ayyubids instead of fortifying themselves in Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] After 1175, rebuilding in a more solid form began, and ever since then Aden has been a popular city attracting sailors and merchants from Egypt, Sindh, Gujarat, East Africa and even China.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] According to Muqaddasi, Persians formed the majority of Aden's population in the 10th century.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] During the Ayyubid period in Yemen, Sanaa and its environs were more hostile to their presence than other regions.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Zaidi tribes were able to defeat the Ayyubids in 1226, but Omar bin Rasul, the founder of the Rasulid state, was able to repel them, so he tightened his control over Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The city regained its position during the days of the Rasulids, so they dug wells and built schools, and Aden flourished commercially.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The kings of Bani Rasul were also merchants and enacted a number of laws and regulations to codify trade in the city.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Banu Tahir were able to control Aden after the Banu Rasool, and the Italian traveller Lodovico di Verthama describes it as one of the most powerful cities seen on Earth during the days of the Tahirids.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In 1513, the Portuguese, led by Afonso de Albuquerque, launched an unsuccessful four-day naval siege of Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Mamluks in Egypt sensed the danger and sent a force led by Hussein al-Kurdi.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The victorious King Amer bin Abdul Wahhab provided great aid to the Kurds, but he suffered a heavy defeat in the Battle of Diu.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Mamluks sent a second fleet, but the victorious king refused to cooperate with the Mamluks because he had succeeded in repelling the Portuguese from Aden without their help.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Hussein al-Kurdi became angry and allied with the Zaidi Imam, who was opposed to the Tahirids, al-Mutawakkil Sharaf al-Din, and the Tahirid cities fell successively, with the exception of Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Ottoman Empire took control of the city in 1538.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Ottomans' goal was to prevent the Portuguese from controlling Aden, so the city witnessed difficult days, in addition to the fact that the port of Mocha gained greater importance at the expense of Aden during the sixteenth century.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The city's population declined and it turned into a small village with a population of no more than 600 people.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] While its population was approximately eighty thousand people during the days of the Rasulid state.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In 1421, China's Ming dynasty Yongle Emperor ordered principal envoy grand eunuch Li Xing and grand eunuch Zhou Man of Zheng He's fleet to convey an imperial edict with hats and robes to bestow on the king of Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The envoys boarded three treasure ships and set sail from Sumatra to the port of Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] This event was recorded in the book *Yingyai Shenglan* by Ma Huan who accompanied the imperial envoy.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] After Ottoman rule, Aden was ruled by the Sultanate of Lahej, under suzerainty of the Zaidi imams of Yemen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The first political intercourse between Lahej and the British took place in 1799, when a naval force was sent from Great Britain, with a detachment of troops from India, to occupy the island of Perim and prevent all communication of the French in Egypt with the Indian Ocean, by way of the Red Sea.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The island of Perim was found unsuitable for troops, and the Sultan of Lahej, Ahmed bin Abdul Karim, received the detachment for some time at Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] He proposed to enter into an alliance and to grant Aden as a permanent station, but the offer was declined.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] A Treaty was, however, concluded with the Sultan in 1802 by Admiral Sir Home Popham, who was instructed to enter into political and commercial alliances with the chief rulers on the Arabian coast of the Red Sea.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The imams relied on the revenues from the port of Mocha, and Aden was not as important as the Abadlahs were.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] At the end of the eighteenth century, Sultan *Fadl al-Abdali* concluded an alliance with the Yafi tribes to rebel against the Zaidi imams and monopolise Aden's revenues equally among them.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Sultan of Lahej got rid of the imams, but he did not fulfil his promise to Yafa.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Zaidi imams did not recognise inheritance and saw fighting for the imamate, so the war between *Al-Nasir Muhammad bin Ishaq* and *Al-Mansur Al-Hussein bin Al-Mutawakkil* prolonged, so Al-Abdali took the opportunity to declare his independence in Lahej and Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The English had been visiting Aden and Mocha from 1609, led by Sir Henry Middleton, who was imprisoned, his ships confiscated, and eight of his men killed.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The British tried to conclude treaties with the Zaidi imams after the Ottomans were expelled from Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] They visited Sanaa and Mocha, but they treated the British ambassador poorly and rejected his offer.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Things were different when the Abdali gained independence from Lahj and Medina.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] They signed a treaty with the British in 1802, stipulating that they build a factory in Crater and allocate a special cemetery for British subjects free of charge.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Abdali wanted protection from the tribes.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Sultan Fadl bin Ali was killed by Yafi' gunmen, then one of the sheikhs of Al-Hujariya invaded Lahj and besieged it for five months.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Al-Awaliq also besieged it with eight thousand fighters, and they did not leave until Sultan Ahmed bin Abdul Karim paid them seven thousand dollars.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Then the Fadl family attacked Aden in 1836.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In 1609 *The Ascension* was the first English ship to visit Aden, before sailing on to Mocha during the fourth voyage of the East India Company.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] British interests in Aden began in 1796 with Napoleon's invasion of Egypt, after which a British fleet docked at Aden for several months at the invitation of the sultan.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The French were defeated in Egypt in 1801, and their privateers were tracked down over the subsequent decade.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] By 1800, Aden was a small village with a population of 600 Arabs, Somalis, Jews, and Indians—housed for the most part in huts of reed matting erected among ruins recalling a vanished era of wealth and prosperity.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] As there was little British trade in the Red Sea, most British politicians until the 1830s had no further interest in the area beyond the suppression of piracy.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] However, a small number of government officials and the East India Company officials thought that a British base in the area was necessary to prevent another French advance through Egypt or Russian expansion through Persia.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The emergence of Muhammad Ali of Egypt as a strong local ruler only increased their concerns.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The governor of Bombay from 1834 to 1838, Sir Robert Grant, was one of those who believed that India could only be protected by preemptively seizing "places of strength" to protect the Indian Ocean.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Red Sea increased in importance after the steamship *Hugh Lindsay* sailed from Bombay to the Suez isthmus in 1830, stopping at Aden with the sultan's consent to resupply with coal.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Although cargo was still carried around the Cape of Good Hope in sailing ships, a steam route to the Suez could provide a much quicker option for transporting officials and important communications.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Grant felt that armed ships steaming regularly between Bombay and Suez would help secure British interests in the region and did all he could to progress his vision.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] After lengthy negotiations due to the costs of investing in the new technology, the government agreed to pay half the costs for six voyages per year and the East India Company board approved the purchase of two new steamers in 1837.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Grant immediately announced that monthly voyages to Suez would take place, despite the fact that no secure coal supplying station had been found.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The British first stationed a coal depot on the island of Socotra in 1834.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] However, due to the lack of suitable infrastructure there, they quickly lost interest in Socotra and turned towards Aden instead.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In 1838, under Muhsin bin Fadl, Lahej ceded 194 km2 (75 sq mi) including Aden to the British.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] On 19 January 1839, the British East India Company landed Royal Marines at Aden to definitively conquer the territory (the so-called Aden Expedition) and stop attacks by pirates against British shipping to India.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In 1850 it was declared a free trade port, with the liquor, salt, arms, and opium trades developing duties as it won all the coffee trade from Mokha.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The port lies about equidistant from the Suez Canal, Bombay, and Zanzibar, which were all important British possessions.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Aden had been an entrepôt and a way-station for ships in the ancient world.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] There, supplies, particularly water, were replenished, so, in the mid-19th century, it became necessary to replenish coal and boiler water.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Thus Aden acquired a coaling station at Steamer Point and Aden was to remain under British control until November 1967.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Until 1937, Aden was governed as part of British India and was known as the Aden Settlement.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Its original territory was enlarged in 1857 by the 13 km2 (5.0 sq mi) island of Perim, in 1868 by the 73 km2 (28 sq mi) Khuriya Muriya Islands, and in 1915 by the 108 km2 (42 sq mi) island of Kamaran.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The settlement would become Aden Province in 1935.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In 1937, the settlement was detached from India and became the Colony of Aden, a British Crown colony.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The change in government was a step towards the change in the official currency unit.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] When British India became independent in 1947, Indian rupees (divided into annas) were replaced in Aden by East African shillings.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The hinterland of Aden and Hadhramaut were also loosely tied to Britain as the Aden Protectorate, which was overseen from Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Aden's location also made it a useful *entrepôt* for mail passing between places around the Indian Ocean and Europe.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Thus, a ship passing from Suez to Bombay could leave mail for Mombasa at Aden for collection (See *Postage stamps and postal history of Aden*).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In December 1947, a three-day riot broke out in reaction to the drafting of the Partition Plan for Palestine.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The riots and their repression by the Aden Protectorate Levies saw the killing of 76–82 Jews, 33 Arabs, 4 Muslim Indians and 1 Somali, in addition to looting and damaging of property.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] After the Suez Crisis in 1956, the British held on to Aden as an outpost in the region for another decade.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The British authorities had already decided to further expand its port shortly before the Suez Canal's 1956 closure.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Aden sent a team of two to the 1962 British Empire and Commonwealth Games in Perth, Western Australia.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In order to stabilise Aden and the surrounding Aden Protectorate from the designs of the Egyptian backed republicans of North Yemen, the British attempted gradually to unite the disparate states of the region in preparation for eventual independence.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] On 18 January 1963, the Colony of Aden was incorporated into the Federation of Arab Emirates of the South against the wishes of North Yemen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The city became the State of Aden and the Federation was renamed the Federation of South Arabia (FSA).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] An insurgency against British administration known as the Aden Emergency began with a grenade attack by the communist National Liberation Front (NLF), against the British High Commissioner on 10 December 1963, killing one person and injuring fifty, and a "state of emergency" was declared.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In 1964, Britain announced its intention to grant independence to the FSA in 1968, but that British troops would remain in Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The security situation deteriorated as NLF and FLOSY (Front for the Liberation of Occupied South Yemen) vied for the upper hand.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In January 1967, there were mass riots between the NLF and their rival FLOSY supporters in the old Arab quarter of Aden town.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] This conflict continued until mid February, despite the intervention of British troops.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] On 20 June 1967, 23 British Army soldiers were ambushed and shot dead by members of Aden Police during the Aden Mutiny in the Crater District.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] During the period there were as many attacks on the British troops by both sides as against each other, culminating in the destruction of an Aden Airways DC3 plane in the air with no survivors.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The increased violence was a determining factor in the British ensuring all families were evacuated more quickly than initially intended, as recorded in *From Barren Rocks to Living Stones*.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] On 30 November 1967, British troops were evacuated, leaving Aden and the rest of the FSA under NLF control.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Royal Marines, who had been the first British troops to arrive in Aden in 1839, were almost the last to leave, followed only by the 10 Airfields Squadron of the Royal Engineers, which left Aden on 13 December 1967.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Helicopters of aircraft carrier HMS *Albion* (R07), part of a Royal Navy task force, lifted off the Royal Marine commandos who had been left to secure the airfield.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Qahtan al-Sha'bi assumed the presidency of the new state, and the sheikhdoms of the Eastern Protectorate of Hadramaut and Al-Mahra were annexed to the new state.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Al-Shaabi took over a new country with a collapsed economy.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Civilian workers and businessmen left, and British support ceased.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The closure of the Suez Canal in 1967 played an important role in the country's economy, as it reduced the number of ships crossing Aden by 75%.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The new state was divided into six governorates on 11 December 1967, in order to end the manifestations of tribalism in the state and ignore the tribal borders between the defunct sheikhdoms.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] On March 20, 1968, Qahtan dismissed all leftist leaders from the government and party membership.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] He was able to put down a rebellion led by leftist factions in the army in May of the same year, and faced new rebellions from leftist parties in July, August and December 1968.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] This is because all Arab countries welcomed the front.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] National Liberation received a cold reception.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Regimes like Egypt wanted to merge the National Front with the Front for the Liberation of Occupied South Yemen, where the leftist section was more numerous than the supporters of the popular Qahtan.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] They wanted a regime that would lead the masses and face the great challenges facing the new state, the most important of which was the bankruptcy of the treasury.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Qahtan al-Shaabi dismissed Interior Minister Muhammad Ali Haitham on 16 June 1969, but the latter, with his ties to the tribes and the army, reassembled the leftist forces that had been dispersed by President Qahtan al-Shaabi, and they were able to place him under house arrest on 22 June.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] A presidential committee was formed from Five people: Salem Rabie Ali, who became president, Muhammad Saleh Al-Awlaki, Ali Antar, Abdel Fattah Ismail, and Muhammad Ali Haitham, who became prime minister.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] This group took an extreme leftist line, declaring its support for the Palestinians and the Dhofar Revolution, and strengthening its relationship with the Soviet Union.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] West Germany severed its relationship with the state due to its recognition of East Germany, and the United States also severed its relationship in October 1969.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The new powers issued a new constitution, nationalised foreign banks and insurance companies, and changed the name of the country to the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen in line with the Marxist–Leninist approach they followed.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] A centrally planned economy was established.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The port of Aden was the largest source of national income for the Republic of South Yemen, but the closure of the Suez Canal by Egypt between 1967 and 1975 – reduced commercial activities in the port.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Salem Rubaya Ali wanted to adopt a practical approach, so he communicated with the President of North Yemen, Ibrahim al-Hamdi, and made attempts to restore normal relations with Western countries.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] During his presidency, relations between South Yemen and Saudi Arabia were established in 1976.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] President Salmin, as he is known, coveted more Soviet support, so the contract with Saudi Arabia worried him.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Soviets pushed them to increase aid, but relations with Saudi Arabia became strained again in 1977 following the assassination of North Yemeni President Ibrahim al-Hamdi.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] It is believed that Salem Rabie Ali orchestrated the assassination of Ahmed Hussein al-Ghashmi in revenge for Ibrahim al-Hamdi.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Salem Rabie Ali was subjected to a quick trial that ended with his execution and Abdel Fattah Ismail assuming the presidency of South Yemen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Relations with North Yemen became tense, due to Fattah's support for the factions opposing Ali Abdullah Saleh, who was more fanatical than his predecessors.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Relations with the Soviet Union became active in an unprecedented way, so the Front War broke out in 1978, in which the Soviet Union and the United States intervened.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Ali Nasser Muhammad was able to force Abd al-Fattah Ismail al-Jawfi to resign for "health reasons", and Ismail was exiled to Moscow two years after he assumed the presidency.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Despite the approach of the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen and its removal of tribal aspects, tribalism remained alive among politicians and the public despite the exposure of its sheikhs.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Tribal and regional favouritism and nepotism remained rife in southern Yemen, as political forces called on their tribal and regional affiliations during crises.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] By January 1986, Aden was torn apart by the rivalry of two factions in the ruling Socialist Party, when President Ali Nasser Muhammad's guards launched a surprise attack on the political party's office in Aden on 13 January 1986.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] This was the beginning of the 1986 civil war in South Yemen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Ali Nasser Muhammad was from Abyan Governorate, while most of those killed in the political party office were from Al-Dhalea and Lahj.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Military brigades from those areas bombed Aden from land and sea, forcing Ali Nasser Muhammad to flee and hundreds of thousands of civilians and soldiers to flee to northern Yemen, including Abd Rabbuh Mansour Hadi.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] This was followed by systematic killings and liquidations against the people of Abyan Governorate, on charges that they were collaborating with Ali Nasser Muhammad.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Nearly ten thousand people were killed, and thousands migrated towards North Yemen, most of whom were from Abyan and Shabwa.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] With the unification of north and south Yemen in 1990, Aden was no longer a national capital but remained the capital of *Aden Governorate* which covered an area similar to that of the Aden Colony.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] On 29 December 1992, Al Qaeda conducted its first known terrorist attack in Aden, bombing the Gold Mohur Hotel, where US servicemen were known to have been staying en route to Somalia for Operation Restore Hope.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] A Yemeni and an Austrian tourist died in the attack.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] That war marked the end of the state of the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen, and Haider Abu Bakr Al-Attas assumed the presidency until May 22, 1990, the unity of South Yemen with North Yemen, and the establishment of the Republic of Yemen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] At that time, Ali Salem al-Beidh was considered Ali Abdullah Saleh's deputy, and Haider Abu Bakr Al-Attas was considered prime minister, and after the 1993 elections.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Conflicts began within the ruling coalition, and Vice President Ali Salem Al-Beidh retreated to Aden in August 1993.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The general security situation in the country deteriorated, and the complete integration of the two armies failed.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The southern forces, which were transferred to Amran, clashed with the northern forces there, and the forces of the northern giants, which were transferred to Amran, clashed.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] At the forefront of these emerged a group of the brightest officers, such as Abd Rabbuh Mansour Hadi, who became Minister of Defense at the time; the former Chief of Staff, Major General Abdullah Aliwa; and Major General Salem Qatan, who was assassinated by an Al-Qaeda gunman.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] After the war, Abd Rabbuh Mansour Hadi was appointed Vice President of the Republic, and remained in office.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] He held his position until 2012, when he was elected president of the country.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Members of al Qaeda attempted to bomb the US guided-missile destroyer *The Sullivans* at the port of Aden as part of the 2000 millennium attack plots.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The boat that had the explosives in it sank, forcing the planned attack to be aborted.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The bombing attack on destroyer USS *Cole* took place in Aden on 12 October 2000.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In 2007 growing dissatisfaction with unification led to the formation of the secessionist South Yemen Movement.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] According to *The New York Times*, the Movement's mainly underground leadership includes socialists, Islamists and individuals desiring a return to the perceived benefits of the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Aden remained in a state of political stagnation for 25 years until President Abd Rabbuh Mansour Hadi took refuge there and carried out his work from the Republican Palace in Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] On 7 March 2015, Hadi declared Aden the temporary capital, instead of Sanaa, which he described as occupied by the Houthis.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] This was after the Houthis took control of Sanaa on 21 September 2014, and imposed a siege on the Republican Palace and the home of President Hadi on 20 January.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] On 22 January, Hadi submitted his resignation to Parliament; it did not hold a session to accept or reject the resignation, and Hadi remained under house arrest imposed by the Houthis.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] President Abd Rabbuh Mansur Hadi fled to Aden, his hometown, in February 2015 after being deposed in the coup d'état that many consider to be the start of the Yemeni civil war.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Others consider that the civil war began in September 2014 when Houthi forces took over the capital city Sanaa, which was followed by a rapid Houthi takeover of the government.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Hadi declared in Aden that he was still Yemen's legitimate president and called on state institutions and loyal officials to relocate to Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In a televised speech on 21 March 2015, he declared Aden to be Yemen's "economic and temporary capital" while Sanaa is controlled by the Houthis.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Aden was hit by violence in the aftermath of the coup d'état, with forces loyal to Hadi clashing with those loyal to former president Ali Abdullah Saleh in a battle for Aden International Airport on 19 March 2015.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] After the airport battle, the entire city became a battleground for the Battle of Aden, which left large parts of the city in ruins and has killed at least 198 people since 25 March 2015.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Some Arab and foreign embassies were transferred to Aden, and Defense Minister Mahmoud Al-Subaihi was able to leave Sanaa for Aden and met with President Hadi.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] On March 4, 2016, unidentified gunmen stormed the Mother Teresa House in the city and killed sixteen people, including four nuns.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] A number of the old city's churches have also been destroyed by Islamic extremists since mid-2015.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] On 14 July 2015, the Saudi Arabian Army launched an offensive to win control of the city.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Within three days, the city was cleared of Houthi rebels, ending the Battle of Aden with a coalition victory.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Beginning on 28 January 2018, separatists loyal to the Southern Transitional Council (STC) seized control of the Yemeni government headquarters in Aden in a coup d'état against the Hadi-led government.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Prime Minister Maeen Abdulmalik Saeed, his ministers and his entourage were conducted to safety under the barrage of hostile fire.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] On 7 January 2026, the Yemeni government forces managed to control Aden following the collapse of the Southern Transitional Council.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The entry of the Yemenis into Islam contributed to their abandoning their ancient script and replacing it with the late Nabataean alphabet in which the Qur'an was written.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Today, Yemenis speak Arabic in the Yemeni dialect, which is a developed dialect and closely linked to the ancient language.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] It has three dialects with branches: the Sanʽani dialect, the Hadrami dialect, and the Taʽizzi-Adeni dialect, in addition to the Bedouin dialect of the residents of Marib.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Al Jawf, Shabwa, and Inner Hadhramaut, and each of these dialects has characteristics and features.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Adeni art or the *Adeniyat* is an art of Arabic music.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Among the ancient artists of Aden are Iskander Thabet Saleh and Muhammad Murshid Naji, and among the poets are Abdul Rahman Ibrahim Muhammad, Ahmed Ghaleb Muhammad Al-Jabri, Abdullah Abdul Karim Muhammad, Ali Abdullah Jaafar Aman, Farid Muhammad Barakat, Lotfi Jaafar Aman, and Mohsen Ali Brik.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] "Adeni music" played a major role in Aden society, and artists in the Aden dialect were called "al-Mutariba", meaning people of music.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Adeni music began in 1920 when the army of the Aden Protectorate was formed, and after it the National Guard, where there were teams for those forces and those teams participated On special occasions and weddings.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The city of Aden is considered the first city in which sports were practiced in the Arabian Peninsula, and the first private club in Aden was founded in 1905 under the name "Al-Ittihad Al-Muhammadi Club", as the first sports club in Yemen and the Arab world.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] He was fighting the occupation army divisions and the fleet divisions coming and passing to the port of Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In 1924, the "Al-Husseini Sports Club" was founded in Crater, and a third club appeared in Tawahi under the name "Al-Bamboot Club" and Sheikh Othman.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The 1930s witnessed the emergence of a number of clubs.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In 1933, the "Nujoom Al-Layl Club", Al-Aidrousi Club, and Nujoom Al-Sabah Club appeared in Crater, and in Tawahi, the "Al-Ittihad Al-Islami Club" (Al-Mawlada) appeared.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Until that year, football matches were played in a friendly manner between the teams of the Crater, Al-Tawahi, and Sheikh Othman regions, as there were no federations regulating sports activity.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In 1934, the occupation authority announced the establishment of a sports association called the "Adeniya Sports Association", after the increasing number of local clubs.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Its members were appointed by the Governor-General of Aden, and all of its members were English, headed by the English Governor of Aden, Bernard Reilly, as sponsor.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The association's board of directors consists of Hikam Bottom as president, the Indian Rosario as secretary, and two other members.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] This association began holding the first club tournament, which was the "Rosario Cup Championship".
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Among the most important tournaments held in Aden before independence were the Rosario Cup, the Riley Cup, the Somali Bassem Al-Nar Cup, the Aramco Cup, and the Kik Muncherji Championship.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] After independence, the "Football Federation" was established on January 18, 1968, on the ruins of the "Adeniya Sports Association".
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] The Federation took a decision regarding the Adeniya clubs, which had numbered about 64 sports clubs, reducing and merging the clubs in Aden and Lahj to only 16 clubs, and the clubs were forced to join or unite with large teams.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In February 1968, several sports clubs were abolished, leaving only 12 clubs remaining.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In December 1968, Al-Islah Club and Al-Shaab Club were merged into one club under the name of the latter in Al-Tawahi.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In 1969, the Al-Ittihad Al-Muhammadi Club and Al-Tadamon Club were united in Crater, under the name Al-Tadamon Al-Muhammadi Club.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In the "First General Sports Conference" in 1973, the clubs were merged and reduced again, so that their number became only 7 clubs: Al-Ahrar Club, Al-Ahly Club, Shamsan Club, Al-Shaab Club, Al-Hilal Club, United Youth Club, and Aden Tennis Club.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] On July 18, 1975, the stage of forming urban clubs, and the beginning of the stage of politicisation of the clubs in favour of the National Liberation Front, took place.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] It was decided to change their names and reduce them to become 5 clubs: Al-Tilal Club, Shamsan Club, Al-Minaa Club, Al-Wahda Club, and Al-Shoula Club.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] On July 18, 1975, the "Al-Tilal Sports Club" appeared, headed by Yassin Saeed Noman, as a new name for the "Al-Ittihad Al-Muhammadi Club", which was founded in 1905, and in 1976 the "Yemeni Football Federation" appeared.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Football is the most popular sport in Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] There are 9 stadiums in Aden, including the May 22 International Stadium, and 10 sports clubs.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] In November 2010, Aden hosted the 2010 Arabian Gulf Football Cup.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p01] Aden has several historical and natural sites of interest to visitors.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The industrial activity in Aden is represented by a group of factories and production units, the forefront of which is the oil refinery.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The oil refinery in Aden is considered one of the first refineries to be established in the region, and began operating in 1954 AD.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The Aden Refineries Company has facilities such as an oil tanker port, a network of storage tanks, and a centre to supply ships with fuel.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Historically, Aden was a station for importing goods from the African coast and from Europe, the United States, and India.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] As of 1920, Aden was a major commercial centre for trade in the Arabian Peninsula, and the port exported small quantities of local products to most Arab ports.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Aden provided coal and salt to passing ships, and the port was a stopping point for ships when they entered Bab al-Mandab.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Historically, the port of Aden was the main transport port in the region.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Passenger ships land in Al-Tawahi District, and the city is served by Aden International Airport, which is about 10 kilometres (6 mi) from the city.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The airport is the main headquarters of Al-Saeeda Airlines and its operations centre.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The airport is considered the second largest airport.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] In Yemen, after Sanaa International Airport, it is considered the best airport in Yemen in terms of location due to the mountainous nature of Yemen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] However, this airport is surrounded by the Arabian Sea in terms of take-off and landing.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The establishment of Aden Airport dates back to the year 1927 when the British forces established a military airport in the district.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] After World War II, Britain carried out extensive urban modernisation and built Aden International Airport, known today, next to the military airport.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Alyemda Airlines was the official carrier of South Yemen, before unification, and was based in Aden, before merging with Yemen Airways in 1996.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Before the Battle of Aden Airport and the 2015 military intervention in Yemen closed this airport along with other airports in Yemen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] On 22 July, Aden International Airport was declared fit for operation again after the Houthi forces were driven from the city, and a Saudi plane carrying aid reportedly became the first plane to land in Aden in four months.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The same day, a ship chartered by the World Food Programme carrying fuel docked in Aden's port.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Historically, Aden's harbour has been a major hub of transportation for the region.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] As of 1920, the harbour was 13 by 6 km (8 by 4 mi) in size.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Passenger ships landed at Steamer Point now called Tawahi.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] During the British colonial period motor vehicles drove on the left, as in the United Kingdom.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] On 2 January 1977, Aden, along with the rest of South Yemen, changed to driving on the right, bringing it into line with neighbouring Arab states.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] During the early 20th century, Aden was a prominent export centre for coffee grown in the Jubail highlands.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] And also to export frankincense, wheat, barley, alfalfa and millet, which are produced and exported from Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The leaves and stems of clover, millet, and corn produced in Aden were generally used as fodder.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Beginning in 1920, Aden was desalinating seawater to produce table salt.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Between 1916 and 1917, Aden produced more than 120,000 tons of salt.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Aden also produced potash, which was exported to Mumbai.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Historically, Aden would import goods from the African coast and from Europe, the United States, and India.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] As of 1920, the British described it as "the chief emporium of Arabian trade, receiving the small quantities of native produce, and supplying the modest wants of the interior and of most of the smaller Arabian ports." At the docks, the city provided coal to passing ships.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The only item being produced by the city, as of 1920, was salt.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Also, the port was the stop ships had to take when entering the Bab-el-Mandeb; this was how cities like Mecca had received goods by ship.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Yemen Airlines, the national airline of South Yemen, had its head office in Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] On 15 May 1996, Yemen Airlines merged with Yemenia.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] During the early 20th century Aden was a notable centre of coffee production.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Women processed coffee beans, grown in the Yemen highlands.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Frankincense, wheat, barley, alfalfa, and millet was also produced and exported from Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The leaves and stalks of the alfalfa, millet and maize produced in Aden were generally used as fodder.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] As of 1920, Aden was also gathering salt from salt water.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] An Italian company called Agostino Burgarella Ajola and Company gathered and process the salt under the name Aden Salt Works.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] There was also a smaller company from India, called Abdullabhoy and Joomabhoy Lalji & Company that owned a salt production firm in Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Between 1916 and 1917, Aden produced over 120,000 tons of salt.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Aden has also produced potash, which was generally exported to Mumbai.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Charcoal was produced as well, from acacia, and mainly in the interior of the region.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Cigarettes were produced by Jewish and Greek populations in Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The tobacco used was imported from Egypt.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Since the outbreak of the Yemeni Civil War spread to Aden in 2015, the city has been struck by constant protests over a range of issues, but especially concerning electricity generation.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Aden's power grid is composed solely of diesel generators and is thus heavily dependent on imported fuel.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The main power plant is al-Hasswa diesel power plant, which in June 2021 had only two turbines out of five running, producing up to 50 megawatts (MW) of power in a region where the deficit hovers around 300 MW.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Nawfal al-Mojamal, the plant director, said "In its 35 years of existence, al-Hasswa station never had any kind of maintenance, except in 2016 ... when the two turbines were restored".
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] This electricity shortage led to the development of Yemen's first large-scale solar power plant servicing Aden with a 120 MW capacity, opened in July 2024.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The free zone, which was opened in 1991, represents Yemen's economic gateway and the meeting point of the continents of Asia and Africa.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The free zone gains its strategic importance from the special location of the port of Aden, as it is located directly on the main trade route around the world and from the Middle East to Europe and America, and is distinguished by the possibility of providing transit services.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] To East Africa, the Red Sea, the Indian subcontinent and the Arabian Gulf.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The free zone represents a storage and distribution area suitable for Africa, the Red Sea and the Arabian Gulf.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Aden is located on the coast of the Gulf of Aden, and is about 363 kilometres from the capital, Sanaa.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] It is located between latitudes 47 and 12 north of the equator, and at an altitude of 6 metres above sea level.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] It is surrounded by Lahj Governorate to the north and east, and the Governorate of Abyan is to the northwest.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Aden has an airport (Aden International Airport), a seaport (the port of Aden), and has land routes from the north linking it to Hajj, Abyan and Taiz.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Aden is a coastal city; it overlooks the Gulf of Aden, which opens to the Indian Ocean.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The shape of the city of Aden in the form of two peninsulas helped this factor to make the city of Aden unique in this particularity, which clearly affected the occurrence of the phenomenon of land and sea breezes.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Which occurs due to air exchange between land and water during the day and night.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Its location on the water surface also affects the daily and annual temperature range.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] This does not mean that there are no significant differences in temperatures in summer and winter.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Aden has a hot desert climate (BWh) in the Köppen-Geiger climate classification system.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Although Aden sees next-to-no precipitation year-round, it is humid throughout the year.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Most of the coasts of Aden Governorate along the coastal strip are sandy coasts, and the governorate has coastal beaches, including the Golden Coast in Al-Tawahi District, the coast of Abyan Bakhour Maksar, Al-Ghadeer Beach, and Kud Al-Nimr Beach in Buraiqa.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] There are about 21 islands around the peninsulas of Aden, Aden Lesser, and Ras Amran.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] They are mostly rocky islands, some of which are surrounded by incomplete coral reefs, and most of them are considered fishing areas.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] A number of islands have many activities, especially on Al-Ummal Island and Sirah Island.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Yemen is considered one of the countries rich in bird species in the Middle East due to the availability of many suitable coastal environments that helped attract many migratory birds to wetland sites, coasts and islands.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The Aden region (Khor Maksar – Al-Haswah) was registered on the list of important areas of the World Bird Organization as a habitat.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The last three species that are globally threatened with extinction are: the great eagle, the gull eagle, and the eastern king eagle.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] There are dozens of bird species recorded in the wetlands of Aden and the Caltex swamp area, which are rich in a wide variety of endemic and migratory birds, including birds that are present throughout the year.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] There are many birds in the area, including great flamingos, dwarf flamingos, and rock egrets.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] And the spoonbill, the hooked tern and the seagull.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] There are 95 schools in Aden, including 13 kindergartens, and 82 basic education schools, including 29 schools for boys, 29 schools for girls, and 29 joint schools for boys and girls.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] There are also 29 secondary schools, including 15 schools for boys and 14 schools for girls, all of which are in a double shift system.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Until 2004, the number of male students reached In basic education, there were 57,941 students and 48,081 female students, with a total of 104,622 students.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] In secondary education, the number of male students reached 11,029 students, and 9,643 female students.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] As for vocational, technical and vocational education centres and institutes, their number is 13, with 2,214 students enrolled, including 453 teachers.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The health institutes have one institute, with 864 students enrolled, including 147 teachers, according to 2010 statistics.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] As for higher education, there is one government university in Aden, which is the University of Aden, which has 9 colleges.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] More than 29 thousand students are enrolled, according to 2010 statistics.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] There are 15 hospitals in the economic capital, Aden, including 5 public government hospitals, 6 belonging to the private sector, and 37 health centres.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] There are 34 facilities in the city that provide maternity and childhood services, and the number of specialised workforce in health facilities is 2,825 specialists.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] In June 2015, the International Red Cross team present in conflict areas in Yemen during the events of the Yemeni civil war announced that the cities of Crater, Al-Mualla, Khor Maksar and Al-Tawahi in the Aden Governorate in the south of the country were areas affected by dengue fever.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The health authorities in Aden said that this fever had spread remarkably and widely.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Since the beginning of May, health services have deteriorated and infrastructure facilities, such as electricity, water, and sanitation, have been damaged as a result of the ongoing fighting in the city for months.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Aden has known mail since June 15, 1839, that is, a year after the British occupation, although the official post office was not inaugurated until 1857.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Postage stamps of both Britain and India were used in Aden until it became called the Aden Colony on April 1, 1937, although the stamps of this stage It bears no distinctive sign, but the use of the number 124 as a postal code is attributed to Aden as part of the Indian postal numerical system.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Then, when it became a colony in 1937, it had sets of postage stamps containing pictures and the name Aden printed on them.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The weekly *Al-Amal* newspaper was founded in 1957 in Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Its slogan was "Freedom, Bread, and Peace".
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The British authorities allowed only 1,500 copies to be printed weekly, and the newspaper was banned shortly afterward.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] In 1958, *Al-Ayyam*, an independent daily newspaper in the Arabic language, was established in Aden during the British occupation.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The first issue was published on 30 July 1958, and its founder and editor-in-chief was Brigadier General Muhammad Ali Bashraheel.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] It stopped publishing after independence during the era of the People's Democratic Republic of Yemen, and then resumed publication.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] After achieving Yemeni unity, the first issue of the second edition was on 7 November 1990, after a hiatus that lasted more than 23 years.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] In 1998, *Al-Ayyam* was the first newspaper in Yemen to be prosecuted by the government under a criminal law.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Other cases followed until it became public by the end of the year.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] 2008, responsible for 73% of the total number of cases filed by the Ministry of Information and the Yemeni government against the press in Yemen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] On 12 May 2009, security forces launched an attack on the headquarters of *Al-Ayyam* newspaper in Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Radio Aden was established on 17 August 1954, under the name "Aden Radio Station".
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] It is currently broadcast in two periods, morning and evening.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] The British occupation opened the Aden Channel on 11 September 1964, following the revolution of 14 October 1963.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] Television transmission was limited to covering populated neighbourhoods in the city of Aden, especially where soldiers and families of the British forces were present.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] In January 1979, the television headquarters moved to the "Radio and Television Building" in Tawahi; at that time broadcasts were in black-and-white.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] In March 1981 the gradual transition to colour broadcasting began, and in June 1981 the channel began broadcasting via satellite.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-p02] After the Yemeni unification on 22 May 1990, Aden Channel was the second official channel of Yemeni TV.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] The **Aden Protectorate** (Arabic: محمية عدن **Maḥmiyyat ‘Adan**) was a British protectorate in southern Arabia.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] The protectorate evolved in the hinterland of the port of Aden and in the Hadhramaut after the conquest of Aden by the Bombay Presidency of British India in January 1839, and which continued until the 1960s.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] In 1940, it was divided for administrative purposes into the Western Protectorate and the Eastern Protectorate.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] The territory now forms part of the Republic of Yemen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] What became known as the Aden Protectorate began with informal arrangements of protection with nine states in the immediate hinterland of the port city of Aden, namely Abdali, Alawi, Amiri, Aqrabi, Aulaqi, Fadhli, Haushabi, Subeihi, and Yafa.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] British expansion into the area was designed to secure the important port that was, at the time, governed from British India.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] Beginning with a formal treaty of protection with the Mahra Sultanate of Qishn and Socotra in 1886, the British began a slow formalisation of protection arrangements that included more than 30 major treaties of protection with the last signed only in 1954.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] These treaties, together with a number of other minor agreements, created the Aden Protectorate that extended well east of Aden to Hadhramaut and included all of the territory that would become South Yemen except for the immediate environs and port of the colonial capital, Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] Aden with its harbour was the only area in full British sovereignty and, together with some offshore islands, was known as Aden Settlement (1839–1932), Aden Province (1932–1937), the Colony of Aden (1937–1963) and finally State of Aden (1963–1967).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] In exchange for British protection, the rulers of the constituent territories of the Protectorate agreed not to make treaties with or cede territory to any other foreign power.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] In 1917, control of Aden Protectorate was transferred from the Government of India, which had inherited the British East India Company's interests in various princely states on the strategically important naval route from Europe to India, to the British Foreign Office.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] For administrative purposes, the protectorate was divided into the **Eastern Aden Protectorate** (with its own Political Officer, a British advisor, stationed at Mukalla in Qu'aiti from 1937 to c.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] 1967) and the **Western Aden Protectorate** (with its own Political Officer, stationed at Lahej from 1 April 1937 to 1967), for some separation of administration.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] In 1928, the British established Aden Command, directed by the Royal Air Force, to preserve the security of the Protectorate.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] It was renamed British Forces Aden in 1936 and was known later as British Forces Arabian Peninsula and then Middle East Command (Aden).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] The boundaries between the polities and even their number fluctuated over time.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] Some such as the Mahra Sultanate barely had any functioning administration.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] Not included in the protectorate were Aden Colony and the insular areas of Perim, Kamaran, and Khuriya Muriya that were administered by it.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] In 1938, Britain signed an advisory treaty with the Qu'aiti sultan and, throughout the 1940s and 1950s, signed similar treaties with twelve other protectorate states.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] These agreements allowed for the stationing of a Resident Advisor in the signatory states which gave the British a greater degree of control of their domestic affairs.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] This rationalised and stabilised the rulers' status and laws of succession but had the effect of encouraging official corruption.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] Aerial bombardment and collective punishment were sometimes used against wayward tribes to enforce the rule of Britain's clients.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] British protection came to be considered by some to be an impediment to progress, especially by promoters of Arab nationalism as reinforced by news from the outside received by newly available transistor radios.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] British control was also challenged by King Ahmad bin Yahya of the Mutawakkilite Kingdom of Yemen to the north who did not recognise British suzerainty in South Arabia and had ambitions of creating a unified Greater Yemen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] During the late 1940s and the early 1950s, Yemen was involved with a series of border skirmishes along the disputed Violet Line, a 1914 Anglo-Ottoman demarcation that served to separate Yemen from the Aden Protectorate.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] In 1950, Kennedy Trevaskis, the Advisor for the Western Protectorate developed a plan for the protectorate states to form two federations, corresponding to the two halves of the protectorate.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] Although little progress was made with the plan, it was considered a provocation by Ahmad bin Yahya.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] In addition to his role as king, he also served as the imam of the ruling Zaidi branch of Shi'a Islam.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] He feared that a successful federation in the Shafi'i Sunnite protectorates would serve to encourage discontented Shafi'ites who inhabited the coastal regions of Yemen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] To counter the threat, Ahmad increased Yemeni efforts to decrease British control and, during the mid-1950s, Yemen assisted a number of revolts by disgruntled tribes against protectorate states.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] The appeal of Yemen was limited initially in the protectorate but a growing intimacy between Yemen and the popular Arab nationalist president of Egypt Gamal Abdel Nasser and the formation of United Arab States increased its attraction.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] Aden had been of interest to Britain as a link to British India and then, after the loss of most of Britain's colonies from 1945 and the disastrous Suez Crisis in 1956, as a valuable port for accessing crucial Middle Eastern oil.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] It had also been chosen as the new location for Middle East Command.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] Nationalist pressure prodded the threatened rulers of the Aden Protectorate states to revive efforts at forming a federation and, on 11 February 1959, six of them signed an accord forming the *Federation of Arab Emirates of the South*.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] During the next three years, they were joined by nine others and, on 18 January 1963, Aden Colony was merged with the federation creating the new *Federation of South Arabia*.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] At the same time, the (mostly eastern) states that had not joined the federation became the *Protectorate of South Arabia*, thus ending the existence of the Protectorate of Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] On 10 December 1963, a state of emergency was declared in the former protectorate and the newly created State of Aden.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] The Emergency was caused largely by Arab nationalism spreading to the Arabian Peninsula, encouraged especially by the Socialist and pan-Arabist doctrines of the Egyptian president Gamel Abdel Nasser.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] The British, French, and Israeli invasion forces that had invaded Egypt after Nasser's nationalisation of the Suez Canal in 1956 had been forced to withdraw after intervention from both the United States and the USSR.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] Nasser had only limited success in spreading his pan-Arabist doctrines through the Arab world, with his 1958 attempt to unify Egypt and Syria as the United Arab Republic ending in failure only 3 years later.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] An anti-colonial uprising in Aden in 1963 provided another potential opportunity for his doctrines, though it is not clear whether the revolt among the Arabs in Aden had the Yemeni guerrilla groups drawing inspiration from Nasser's pan-Arabist ideas or acting independently themselves.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] By 1965, the RAF station (RAF Khormaksar) was operating nine squadrons.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] These included transport units with helicopters and a number of Hawker Hunter ground attack aircraft.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] They were called in by the army for strikes against positions using "60 lb" high explosive rockets and 30 mm Aden cannon.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] The Battle of Crater brought Lt-Col Colin Campbell Mitchell (AKA "Mad Mitch") to prominence.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] On 20 June 1967 there was a mutiny in the Army of South Arabian Federation, which spread to the police.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] Order was restored by the British, due mainly to the efforts of the 1st Battalion Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders, commanded by Lt-Col Mitchell.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/aden-protectorate] Nevertheless, deadly guerrilla attacks particularly by the NLF resumed soon against British forces, with the British leaving Aden by the end of November 1967, earlier than had been planned by British Prime Minister Harold Wilson and without an agreement for the succeeding governance.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means re-establishing forest that have either been cut down or lost due to natural causes, such as fire, storm, etc.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Nowadays, the boundaries between afforestation and reforestation projects can be blurred as it may not be so clear what was there before at what point in time.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] An essential aspect of successful afforestation efforts lies in the careful selection of tree species that are well-suited to the local climate and soil conditions.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] By choosing appropriate species, afforested areas can better withstand the impacts of climate change.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Planting and protecting them would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon which is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's current carbon pool.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] However, there has been debate about whether afforestation is beneficial for the sustainable use of natural resources, with some researchers pointing out that tree planting is not the only way to enhance climate mitigation and CO2 capture.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Non-forest areas, such as grasslands and savannas, also benefit the biosphere and humanity, and they need a different management strategy - they are not supposed to be forests.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Afforestation critics argue that ecosystems without trees are not necessarily degraded, and many of them can store carbon as they are; for example, savannas and tundra store carbon underground.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Carbon sequestration estimates in these areas often do not include the total amount of carbon reductions in soils and slowing tree growth over time.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Afforestation can also negatively affect biodiversity by increasing fragmentation and edge effects on the habitat outside the planted area.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Australia, Canada, China, India, Israel, United States and Europe have afforestation programs to increase carbon dioxide removal in forests and in some cases to reduce desertification.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The term afforestation means establishing new forest on lands that were not forest before (e.g. abandoned agriculture).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The same definition in other words states that afforestation is "conversion to forest of land that historically has not contained forests".
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means the "conversion to forest of land that has previously contained forests but that has been converted to some other use".
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Agroforestry (this is essentially an agricultural activity carried out in order to grow harvestable crops such as fruits and nuts).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Tree plantations (carried out in order to produce wood and wood-pulp products; this can be seen as an alternative to cutting down naturally occurring forests).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] However, the term *afforestation* can also "imply the intentional conversion of native non-forest ecosystems to exotic tree cover and violate biodiversity safeguards".
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The process of afforestation begins with site selection.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Several environmental factors of the site must be analyzed, including climate, soil, vegetation, and human activity.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] These factors will determine the quality of the site, what species of trees should be planted, and what planting method should be used.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] After the forest site has been assessed, the area must be prepared for planting.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Preparation can involve a variety of mechanical or chemical methods, such as chopping, mounding, bedding, herbicides, and prescribed burning.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Once the site is prepared, planting can take place.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] One method for planting is direct seeding, which involves sowing seeds directly into the forest floor.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Another is seedling planting, which is similar to direct seeding except that seedlings already have an established root system.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Afforestation by cutting is an option for tree species that can reproduce asexually, where a piece of a tree stem, branch, root, or leaves can be planted onto the forest floor and sprout successfully.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Sometimes special tools, such as a tree planting bar, are used to make planting of trees easier and faster.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] There are several benefits from afforestation such as carbon sequestration, increasing rainfall, prevention of topsoil erosion (from water and wind), flood and landslide mitigation, barriers against high winds, shelter for wildlife, employment and alternative sources of wood products.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Afforestation projects create employment opportunities, particularly in rural areas, thus promoting sustainable livelihoods.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] They can create many jobs in various forest-related activities.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Forests are an important part of the global carbon cycle because trees and plants absorb carbon dioxide through photosynthesis.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Therefore, they play an important role in climate change mitigation.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] By removing the greenhouse gas CO2 from the air, forests function as terrestrial carbon sinks, meaning they store large amounts of carbon in the form of biomass, encompassing roots, stems, branches, and leaves.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] By doing so, forests sequester approximately 25% of human carbon emissions annually, playing a critical role in Earth's climate.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Throughout their lifespan, trees continue to sequester carbon, storing atmospheric CO2 long-term.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Sustainable forest management, afforestation, reforestation are therefore important contributions to climate change mitigation.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] An important consideration in such efforts is that forests can turn from sinks to carbon sources.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In 2019 forests took up a third less carbon than they did in the 1990s, due to higher temperatures, droughts and deforestation.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] National-scale forest inventory data also shows trends from 1999 to 2020 that some forests were already approaching climate thresholds shifting them from carbon sinks to carbon sources.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The typical tropical forest may become a carbon source by the 2060s.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Researchers have found that, in terms of environmental services, it is better to avoid deforestation than to allow for deforestation to subsequently reforest, as the latter leads to irreversible effects in terms of biodiversity loss and soil degradation.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Furthermore, the probability that legacy carbon will be released from soil is higher in a younger boreal forest.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In particular, boreal forests have been noted to support the growth of Armillaria (honey fungus), which is a root pathogen that breaks down compounds necessary for wood integrity, increasing the likelihood of carbon release.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Global greenhouse gas emissions caused by damage to tropical rainforests may have been substantially underestimated until around 2019.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Additionally, the effects of afforestation and reforestation will be farther in the future than keeping existing forests intact.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] It takes much longer − several decades − for the benefits for global warming to manifest to the same carbon sequestration benefits from mature trees in tropical forests and hence from limiting deforestation.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Therefore, scientists consider "the protection and recovery of carbon-rich and long-lived ecosystems, especially natural forests" to be "the major climate solution".
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The planting of trees on marginal crop and pasture lands helps to incorporate carbon from atmospheric CO 2 into biomass.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] For this carbon sequestration process to succeed the carbon must not return to the atmosphere from biomass burning or rotting when the trees die.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Several species of *Ficus* such as *Ficus wakefieldii* have been observed to sequester atmospheric CO2 as calcium oxalate in the presence of oxalotrophic bacteria and fungi, which catabolize the oxalate, which produces calcium carbonate.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The calcium carbonate is precipitated throughout the tree, which also alkalinizes the surrounding soil.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] These species are current candidates for carbon sequestration in agroforestry.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] This Calcium-oxalate fixation process was first observed in the *Iroko* tree, which can sequester up to a ton of calcium carbonate in the soil over its lifespan.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Also Cacti, such as the *Saguaro*, transfer carbon from the biological cycle to the geological cycle by forming the mineral calcium carbonate.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover, although this estimate has been criticized, and the true area that has a net cooling effect on the climate when accounting for biophysical feedbacks like albedo is 20-80% lower.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Planting and protecting these trees would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon if the trees survive future climate stress to reach maturity.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] To put this number into perspective, this is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions (as of 2019) .
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's carbon pool in 2019.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Life expectancy of forests varies throughout the world, influenced by tree species, site conditions, and natural disturbance patterns.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In some forests, carbon may be stored for centuries, while in other forests, carbon is released with frequent stand replacing fires.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Forests that are harvested prior to stand replacing events allow for the retention of carbon in manufactured forest products such as lumber.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] However, only a portion of the carbon removed from logged forests ends up as durable goods and buildings.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The remainder ends up as sawmill by-products such as pulp, paper, and pallets.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] If all new construction globally utilized 90% wood products, largely via adoption of mass timber in low rise construction, this could sequester 700 million net tons of carbon per year.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] This is in addition to the elimination of carbon emissions from the displaced construction material such as steel or concrete, which are carbon-intense to produce.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] A meta-analysis found that mixed species plantations would increase carbon storage alongside other benefits of diversifying planted forests.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Although a bamboo forest stores less total carbon than a mature forest of trees, a bamboo plantation sequesters carbon at a much faster rate than a mature forest or a tree plantation.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Therefore, the farming of bamboo timber may have significant carbon sequestration potential.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that: "The total carbon stock in forests decreased from 668 gigatonnes in 1990 to 662 gigatonnes in 2020".
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In Canada's boreal forests as much as 80% of the total carbon is stored in the soils as dead organic matter.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Impacts on temperature are affected by the location of the forest.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] For example, reforestation in boreal or subarctic regions has less impact on climate.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] This is because it substitutes a high-albedo, snow-dominated region with a lower-albedo forest canopy.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] By contrast, tropical reforestation projects lead to a positive change such as the formation of clouds.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] These clouds then reflect the sunlight, lowering temperatures.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Planting trees in tropical climates with wet seasons has another advantage.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In such a setting, trees grow more quickly (fixing more carbon) because they can grow year-round.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Trees in tropical climates have, on average, larger, brighter, and more abundant leaves than non-tropical climates.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] A study of the girth of 70,000 trees across Africa has shown that tropical forests fix more carbon dioxide pollution than previously realized.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The research suggested almost one-fifth of fossil fuel emissions are absorbed by forests across Africa, Amazonia and Asia.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Afforestation provides other environmental benefits, including increasing the soil quality and its organic carbon levels, reducing the risk of erosion and desertification.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The planting of trees in urban areas is also able to reduce air pollution via the trees' absorption and filtration of pollutants, including carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide, and ozone, in addition to CO2.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Afforestation protects the biodiversity of plants and animals which allows the sustenance of ecosystems that provide clean air, soil fertilization, etc.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Forests support biodiversity conservation, providing habitats for about 80% of the world's biodiversity and contributing to ecosystem restoration and resilience.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Water management can be improved afforestation, as trees regulate hydrological cycles, reduce soil erosion, and prevent water runoff.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Their capacity to capture and store water helps in mitigating floods and droughts.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Forests act as natural air filters, absorbing pollutants and improving air quality.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Urban forestation projects have been successful in reducing respiratory illnesses and enhancing overall air quality in cities.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Trees provide shade and cooling effects.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] By shading and evaporation, forests can lower local temperatures, offering a more comfortable environment in urban areas and reducing the impact of extreme heat.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Tree-planting campaigns are criticised for sometimes targeting areas where forests would not naturally occur, such as grassland and savanna biomes.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Carbon sequestration forecasts of afforestation programmes often insufficiently consider possible carbon reductions in soils as well as slowing tree growth over time.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Afforestation can negatively affect biodiversity through increasing fragmentation and edge effects for the habitat remaining outside the planted area.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] New forest plantations can introduce generalist predators that would otherwise not be found in open habitat into the covered area, which could detrimentally increase predation rates on the native species of the area.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] A study by scientists at the British Trust for Ornithology into the decline of British populations of Eurasian curlew found that afforestation had impacted curlew populations through fragmentation of their naturally open grassland habitats and increases in generalist predators.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Questions have also been raised in the scientific community regarding how global afforestation could affect the surface albedo of Earth.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The canopy cover of mature trees could make the surface albedo darker, which causes more heat to be absorbed, potentially raising the temperature of the planet.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] This is particularly relevant in parts of the world with high levels of snow cover, due to the significant difference in albedo between highly reflective white snow and darker forest cover which absorbs more solar radiation.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] One significant criticism of reforestation or afforestation efforts that rely on monocultures of - usually conifer - trees is that, while they may increase tree cover, they fail to provide the diverse and complex habitat needed by most woodland creatures.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Monocultures, often planted for commercial purposes or ease of management, lack the biodiversity of natural forests.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] These single-species forests provide limited food sources, shelter, and nesting sites for a wide range of wildlife, and in purely coniferous forests low levels of light may reach the forest floor reducing habitat and variety of plant life.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Many woodland creatures, such as birds, mammals, and insects, rely on a variety of tree species and plant life for survival, and the uniformity of monocultures does not support these varied ecological needs.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] As a result, such reforestation or afforestation efforts may unintentionally create environments that are unsuitable for the very species they aim to protect, thus undermining broader conservation goals.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The Great Green Wall of Africa is a ~5,000 mile forest being planted across the continent to stop the spread of the Sahara Desert to the south.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In Adelaide, South Australia (a city of 1.3 million as of June 2016), Premier Mike Rann (2002 to 2011) launched an urban forest initiative in 2003 to plant 3 million native trees and shrubs by 2014 on 300 project sites across the metro area.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Thousands of Adelaide citizens participated in community planting days on sites including parks, reserves, transport corridors, schools, water courses and coastline.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Only native trees were planted to ensure genetic integrity.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Rann said the project aimed to beautify and cool the city and make it more livable, improve air and water quality, and reduce Adelaide's greenhouse gas emissions by 600,000 tonnes of CO2 per year.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In 2003, the government of Canada created a four-year project called the Forest 2020 Plantation Development and Assessment Initiative, which involved planting 6000 ha of fast-growing forests on non-forested lands countrywide.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] These plantations were used to analyze how afforestation can help to increase carbon sequestration and mitigate greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions while also considering the economic and investment attractiveness of afforestation.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] On 14 December 2020, Canada's Minister of Natural Resources Seamus O'Regan announced the federal government's investment of $3.16 billion to plant two billion trees over the next 10 years.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] This plan aims to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by an estimated 12 megatonnes by 2050.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] China had the highest afforestation rate of any country or region in the world, with 4.77 million hectares (47,000 square kilometers) of afforestation in 2008.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] According to the 2021 government work report, forest coverage will reach 24 percent based on the main targets and tasks for the 14th Five-Year Plan period.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] A law in China from 1981 requires that every school student over the age of 11 plants at least one tree per year.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] From 2011 to 2016, the city Dongying in Shandong province forested over 13,800 hectares of saline soil through the Shandong Ecological Afforestation Project, which was launched with support from the World Bank.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In 2017, the Saihanba Afforestation Community won the UN Champions of the Earth Award in the Inspiration and Action category for "transforming degraded land into a lush paradise".
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The successful afforestation of the Loess Plateau involved collaborative efforts by international and domestic professionals alongside villagers.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Through this initiative, millions of villagers across four of China's poorest provinces were able to improve farming practices and increase incomes and employment, alleviating poverty.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In addition, the careful selection of trees ensured a healthy, self-sustainable ecosystem between tree and soil which facilitated a net carbon sink.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The Loess Plateau, although successful, was costly, reaching almost US$500 million.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] This contrasts with more recent initiatives where the results have not been as favorable.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In an attempt to make afforestation both low-cost and less time-consuming, China shifted towards monoculture of mostly red pine trees.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] However, this did not adequately take into consideration environmental structure and led to increased soil erosion, desertification, sand/dust storms and short-lived trees.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] This has reduced China's environmental sustainability index (ESI) to one of the lowest in the world.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Regarding the effects of afforestation on long-term carbon stocks and carbon sequestration these decrease when trees are less than 5 years old and increase quickly thereafter.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] This means trees from monoculture planting that do not survive never reach full potential for carbon sequestration to offset China's carbon output.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Overall, there is a possibility for afforestation to balance carbon levels and aid carbon neutrality, but several challenges still remain which hinder an all encompassing effort.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The Chinese government requires mining companies to restore the environment around exhausted mines by refilling excavated pits and planting crops or trees.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Many mining companies use these recovered mines for ecotourism business.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Europe deforested more than half of its forested areas over the last 6000 years.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The European Union (EU) has paid farmers for afforestation since 1990, offering grants to turn farmland into forest and payments for the management of forest.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] As part of the Green Deal, the EU program "3 Billion Tree Planting Pledge by 2030" provides direction on afforestation of previous farmland in addition to reforestation.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] According to Food and Agriculture Organization statistics, Spain had the third fastest afforestation rate in Europe in the 1990–2005 period, after Iceland and Ireland.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In those years, a total of 44,360 square kilometers were afforested, and the total forest cover rose from 13.5 to 17.9 million hectares.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In 1990, forests covered 26.6% of the Spanish territory.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] As of 2007, that figure had risen to 36.6%.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Spain today has the fifth largest forest area in the European Union.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] As of 2023 the total forest and tree cover in India was 22%.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The forests of India are grouped into 5 major categories and 16 types based on biophysical criteria.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] 38% of the forest is categorized as subtropical dry deciduous and 30% as tropical moist deciduous and other smaller groups.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In 2016 the Indian government passed the CAMPA (Compensatory Afforestation Fund Management and Planning Authority) law, allowing about 40 thousand crores rupees (almost $6 Billion) to go to Indian states for planting trees.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In 2016 the Maharashtra government planted almost 20,000,000 saplings and pledged to plant another 30,000,000 the following year.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In 2019, 220 million trees were planted in a single day in the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] With wood production as a main objective, monocultures of Aleppo pine were vigorously planted between 1948 and the 1970s.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Following a massive collapse of this species in the 1990s, due to attacks by the insect pine blast scale, the Aleppo pine was gradually replaced by Pinus brutia.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Since the 1990s there has been a trend towards more ecological approaches planting mixed forests combining pines with broadleaf Mediterranean species e.g. oak, pistachio, carob, olive, arbutus and buckthorn.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] About 250 million trees have been planted through the JNF across Israel since 1990.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Tree coverage increased from 2% in 1948 to over 8% at present.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The Japanese temperate rainforest is well sustained and maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] One method that has been utilized in maintaining the health of forests in Japan has been afforestation.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The Japanese government and private businesses have set up multiple projects to plant native tree species in open areas scattered throughout the country.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] This practice has resulted in shifts in forest structure and a healthy temperate rainforest that maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In January 2013, the UK government set a target of 12% woodland cover in England by 2060, up from the then 10%.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In Wales the National Assembly for Wales has set a target of 19% woodland cover, up from 15%.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Government-backed initiatives such as the Woodland Carbon Code are intended to support this objective by encouraging corporations and landowners to create new woodland to offset their carbon emissions.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Charitable groups such as Trees for Life (Scotland) contribute to afforestation and reforestation efforts in the UK.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Afforestation efforts in Scotland have provided an increase in woodland expansion.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] By the 20th century mark, Scotland had diminished woodland coverage to 5% of Scotland's land area.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] However, by the early 21st century, afforestation efforts have increased woodland coverage to 17%.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The Scottish government released their Draft Climate Change Plan in January 2017.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] The 2017 draft plan has increased the targeted woodland coverage to 21% by 2032 and increases the afforestation rate to 15,000 hectares per year.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] In the 1800s people moving westward in the US encountered the Great Plains – land with fertile soil, a growing population and a demand for timber but with few trees to supply it.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] So tree planting was encouraged along homesteads.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Arbor Day was founded in 1872 by Julius Sterling Morton in Nebraska City.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] By the 1930s the Dust Bowl environmental disaster signified a reason for adding significant new tree cover.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/afforestation] Public works programs under the New Deal saw the planting of 18,000 miles of windbreaks stretching from North Dakota to Texas to fight soil erosion (see Great Plains Shelterbelt).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] In 1968 Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan, the late Ruler of Abu Dhabi and President of the United Arab Emirates joined efforts and decided on founding a national zoo.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] This decision was born out of their genuine concern of the land's wildlife.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] In 1969 it was established by Shaikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al Nahyan and in 1972 it opened to the public.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] Among the species they wanted to protect were ungulates such as the Arabian oryx.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] Today, the zoo hosts over 4,000 animals, some of them extinct in the wild, some endangered.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] It features a big cat house containing lions, mountain lions, jaguars, black panthers, leopards, and cheetahs.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] In addition, it has a reptile house, monkey compounds, an aquarium, and an aviary.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] From February 2010 until July 2010, the Al Ain Zoo hosted the "Dinosaur Trail," a small section that includes around 15 to 20 mechanical dinosaurs with sensors, such as *Tyrannosaurus rex.* It included information about each dinosaur, living habits, natural habitat and basic features.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] In April 2019 the zoo began its expansion program in order to build new compounds' areas and sites, such as the conservation and breeding centres, African Safari, World Desert Zoo, and the Sheikh Zayed Desert Learning Centre.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] In March 2022, as the zoo intended to import wild African elephants from Namibia, the World Association of Zoos and Aquariums published its thoughts on the matter.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] They stated that according to their Code of Ethics it is essential from time to time to make such actions.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] This is needed in light of global efforts of conservation breeding programs, education programs, or basic biological studies.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] Having said that, they continued their statement that concluded that the zoo's intention to import African elephants does not meet WAZA's Code of Ethics.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] The outcome of that statement was the decision to terminate Al Ain Zoo membership in WAZA until further notice.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] Following that event and statement, on September 15, 2022, the European Association of Zoos and Aquaria (EAZA) also announced the termination of the membership of Al Ain Zoo in the United Arab Emirates.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] The zoo’s membership ended on December 31, 2022, following the decision of the EAZA Council that EAZA can no longer reasonably be expected to allow the institution to remain a member.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] The decision comes after careful examination of evidence related to importing wild-caught African elephants from Namibia, which the Council agreed constituted multiple breaches of EAZA Codes and Standards.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain-zoo] On August 14th it was reported that for the first time in years three Arabian sand cats were born in the zoo.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al Ain is known as the "Garden City" (Arabic: مَدِيْنَة ٱلْحَدِيْقَة, romanized: *Madīnat Al-Ḥadīqah*, lit.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] 'City of The Garden') of Abu Dhabi, the UAE or the Gulf, due to its greenery, particularly with regard to the city's oases, parks, tree-lined avenues and decorative roundabouts, with strict height controls on new buildings, to no more than seven floors.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] According to one author, the oases around Al Ain and Al-Hasa in Saudi Arabia are the most important in the region of the Gulf.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The city is located approximately 160 kilometres (99 mi) east of the capital Abu Dhabi, and about 120 kilometres (75 mi) south of Dubai.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The eastern region covers an area of approximately 13,100 km2 (5,100 sq mi).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Oman lies to the east, Dubai and Sharjah to the north, Abu Dhabi to the west and the Empty Quarter desert and Saudi Arabia to the south.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The topography of Al Ain is unique and varies as one travels to the east.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The ecologically important *Jebel Hafeet* ("Mount Hafeet"), an outlier of the main Hajar range, is considered one of the monuments of Al Ain, lying just to the south of the city.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Rising to 1,100–1,400 metres (3,600–4,600 feet) in elevation, Jebel Hafeet is one of the highest mountains in the country, and has a number of ridges which stretch to the inner part of the city, two of which are *Jabal Al Naqfah* (which touches Al Ain Oasis), and the Western ridge.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Sand dunes of varying texture that are tinged red with iron oxide lie to the north and east of Al Ain.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The city has a hot desert climate (Köppen climate classification *BWh*), featuring long, extremely hot summers and warm winters.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] In Al-Ain, the mean annual rainfall is 96 mm (3.8 in) and the average relative humidity is 60% (United Arab Emirates University, 1993).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Low humidity in Al-Ain, particularly during the summers, makes it a popular destination for many people during this time of the year.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Boer (1997) classified the UAE climate as hyper-arid and divided it into four climatic regions: the coastal zone along the Persian Gulf, the mountain areas northeast of UAE, the gravel plains around Al Ain, and the central and southern sand desert.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] More rainfall and lower temperature occur in the northeast than in the southern and western regions.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The monthly average rainfall around Al-Ain was 100–120 mm (3.9–4.7 in) from the period 1970 to 1992.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] To the south of the city, near Oman, there is the man-made Lake Zakher, which resulted from the release of waste water from desalination plants.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Also in this region, to the east of Jebel Hafeet, lies the area of Mezyad, which has a border crossing with Oman, and is where the historic Mezyad Fort is located.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] With a population of 846,787 (as of 2021), it has the highest percentage of Emirati nationals (30.8%) in the country, though the majority of its residents are expatriates, particularly from the Indian subcontinent.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Many people are from Bangladesh and Pakistan.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] There is also a significant number of Afghans in the city.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al Ain is an important services centre for a wide area extending into Oman.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] There are three major shopping centres, Al Ain Mall, Al Jimi Mall, (with an IKEA store implemented into the mall) Al Hili Mall and Al Bawadi Mall (opened in 2009 in Al Khrair area) as well as traditional souqs for fruit and vegetables and livestock , the road which leads to Mezyad.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Industry is growing on a small scale, and includes the Coca-Cola bottling plant and the Al Ain Portland Cement Works.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Service industries such as car sales, mechanics and other artisans are located in the area known as Sanaiya and Pattan Market.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Social and governmental infrastructure include the Higher Colleges of Technology, well-equipped medical facilities including the teaching hospital at Tawam, Al Ain International Airport, and military training areas.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al Ain also has world's largest dates processing and marketing company, Al Foah Company LLC.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The place is also famous for Al Ain Dairy Farm located just outside Al Ain.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The region of Al Ain and Buraimi, together known as the Buraimi Oasis, is of cultural and historical importance.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] For example, the area witnessed events relevant to the history of Islam during the Rashidun, Umayyad and Abbasid eras, similar to Dibba and Ras Al-Khaimah.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] It was at this place Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan, the founder of the United Arab Emirates, had spent considerable time of his life (approximately from 1927 till he became the Ruler of the Emirate of Abu Dhabi in 1966).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Though it is often said that he was born in Abu Dhabi, some others were of the opinion that he was born in Al-Ain.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al-Ain could also be the place for the oldest mosque in the country, which is in the premises of the Sheikh Khalifa Mosque.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Part of the historically important Western Hajar region, the area of Al Ain has been inhabited for nearly 8,000 years, with archaeological sites showing human settlement at places like Rumailah, Hili and Jabel Ḥafeet.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The early Hafit culture built "beehive" tombs for their dead and engaged in hunting and gathering in the area.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The oases provided water for early farms until the modern age.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] In the 1950s, Sheikh Zayed discovered the tombs, and brought this to the attention of a Danish team, leading to an excavation at the tombs in 1959.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] In 1971, Al Ain Museum was built to house items from this area.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] In the 2000s, the Abu Dhabi Authority for Culture & Heritage lobbied for its recognition as a World Heritage Site by UNESCO, and in 2011, Al Ain became the first World Heritage Site in the UAE to be recognized by UNESCO.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Bronze Age burial sites often re-used materials from earlier burials.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] For instance, the Wadi Suq communal tomb at Qattara Oasis is thought to have been constructed from stones recovered from previous Umm Al Nar burials.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Finds at Qattara include Wadi Suq era chlorite jugs and bowls and late Bronze Age short swords and daggers.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Artefacts recovered also include carnelian jewellery, often associated by UAE historians with trading links to the Indus Valley.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] A find of particular interest from Qattara is a Bronze Age pendant discovered in the 1970s depicting a double-bodied or entwined pair of horned animals.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Made from electrum, an alloy of silver and gold, the motif is found repeated in a number of Bronze Age sites in the UAE.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Iron Age finds in and around Al Ain include *aflaj* (underground water channels) in Bidaa bint Saud, Al Ain and Buraimi which have been placed several centuries prior to the qanats of the Achaemenid Empire, which had previously been credited with the innovation.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al Ain was originally within the area of influence of the Dhawahir, a Bedouin tribe who settled Dhahirah before Buraimi.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] A later wave of settlers, the Na'im, have long had an uneasy relationship with the Dhawahir and the two tribes were frequently in dispute.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Numbering 4,500, the Dhawahir consists of three subsections: the Daramikah, who populated Hili, Mutared and Qattara; the Jawabir in Al Ain and the Bani Saad who lived in Jimi.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Staying in the villages for the summer date season, in winter the community would move throughout the Trucial States.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] A number of interests jostled for influence over the tribes of Buraimi, including the Sultan of Muscat, the Wahhabis (who had made a number of incursions) and the Sheikhs of the Trucial States, particularly the Bani Yas of Abu Dhabi, who acquired large tracts of land, principally from the Dhawahir.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] This suzerainty over Al Ain was cemented by Sheikh Zayed bin Khalifa Al Nahyan, known as 'Zayed the Great', a strong and charismatic leader who took the Dhawahir's main settlement 'Ain Dhawahir (the original name of Al Ain) when the tribe rebelled against him in 1877.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] He built a fort, one of a number of fortifications established by the various interests vying for control over the oasis, to underline his dominion over the oasis and established a *wali*, appointing a member of the Dhawahir as his headman.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Wilfred Thesiger visited Al Ain in the late 1940s, during his travels across the Empty Quarter.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] He met Sheikh Zayed and stayed with him at Al Muwaiji Fort.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] An ongoing dispute between Saudi Arabia, Abu Dhabi and Oman led to the Buraimi Dispute, a series of incidents which saw a Saudi armed force enter the oasis.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Forces from the Trucial Oman Scouts, as well as the army of Muscat-Oman, arrived to recapture the oasis.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] With British intervention, the Saudi forces surrendered, leaving the oasis back in the hands of Abu Dhabi and Oman.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] In 1979, Queen Elizabeth II visited the Al Ain Hilton during her tour of the Persian Gulf.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Following independence in 1971, Al Ain experienced rapid growth and investment as part of the emirate of Abu Dhabi, quickly becoming larger and more successful than Oman's Al-Buraimi.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] In 1972, Oman and Abu Dhabi agreed on the final borders to divide Buraimi and Al Ain.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Until Sheikh Zayed's death in 2004, Al Ain's municipal code forbade construction of buildings over four stories, with the exceptions of the Hilton (now Radisson Blu), Danat Al Ain Resort, and Rotana hotels.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Until 2006, Buraimi and Al Ain shared an open border.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] This border was closed in November 2006, and passport controls were imposed.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The city's *wāḥāt* (Arabic: وَاحَات, lit.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] 'oases') are known for their underground irrigation system (*falaj* or *qanāt*) that brings water from boreholes to water farms and palm trees.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Falaj irrigation is an ancient system dating back thousands of years, and is used widely in Oman, the UAE, China, Iran and other countries.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The largest is Al Ain Oasis, near Old Sarooj, and the smallest is Al-Jahili Oasis.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The rest are Al Qattara, Al-Muʿtaredh, Al-Jimi, Al-Muwaiji, and Hili.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Examples of *aflaj* include *Falaj Hazza*, which is named after Sheikh Zayed's elder brother, Hazza bin Sultan Al Nahyan, and has a district in Al Ain named after it.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The city is known for its combination of modern and pre-modern buildings.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The latter offer an insight into the city's and country's cultural heritage.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The city used to have roundabouts in every intersection but recently these have been replaced by traffic signals.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al-Ain is home to the main federal university in the UAE, the United Arab Emirates University, and to two campuses of the Higher Colleges of Technology – Al Ain Men's College and Al Ain Women's College.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al-Ain is also the home of Horizon International flight academy, Etihad Airways's cadet pilot training centre.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Private higher education institutions include the Al Ain University and campus of Abu Dhabi University.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al-Ain also houses the eastern zone headquarters of the Abu Dhabi Department of Education and Knowledge, Abu Dhabi's education authority.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al-Ain's first formal school, Al Nahyaneia Model School, was founded by Sheikh Zayed in 1959.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Many of Al-Ain's private schools, catering mainly to the expatriate population, are located in the Al-Manaseer area.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Other private schools include the CBSE affiliated school Indian School, Al-Ain, Our Own English High School, Al Adhwa Private School, Brighton College Al Ain and Al Ain Juniors School.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] A new British International School, Belvedere International School is located in the Al Hili district.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] In 1977, the Zayed Central Library was established.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al-Khwarizmi International College has started a Campus at Al-Ain and is offering BBA programme and various other licensed, accredited and approved courses.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The first hospital in Al-Ain was Kanad Hospital (formerly known as Oasis Hospital), established in 1960 by the American missionary couple Drs.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Pat and Marian Kennedy at the invitation of Sheikh Zayed.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] It is the oldest hospital in Al Ain and the second oldest in the United Arab Emirates.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al-Ain is also the home of Tawam Hospital, a training and research hospital linked with the UAE University.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] It was officially inaugurated on 17 December 1979.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] In March 2006, Johns Hopkins Hospital (Johns Hopkins Medicine International) (JHMI) took over the management of Tawam hospital.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Tawam Hospital Archived 20 September 2022 at the Wayback Machine is one of the largest hospitals in the UAE with 503 beds, featuring 24 VIP suites, 78 isolation rooms, 48 ER beds, 9 operating theaters and 81 specialty clinics.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Its oncology centre is the main national cancer treatment centre as well as a regional referral centre.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al Ain Hospital (abbr: AAH, also known as Al-Jimi Hospital) is the general hospital delivering health services to all Al-Ain patients regardless of their nationality.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] It is centrally located in the Al-Jimi district and is linked with the UAE University.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al-Ain Hospital still occupies old 1970s buildings, but a new building is planned.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] AAH currently has about 450 beds and provides services in all medical disciplines.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] In September 2007, the Medical University of Vienna International (MUVI) took over the management of AAH.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Formerly, the city's largest mosque was that of Shaikha Salamah.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] In 2021, the Sheikh Khalifa Grand Mosque became the biggest in the city, as well as one of the largest mosques in the country.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Mary's Catholic Church is located in Al Ain.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al-Ain is connected via the Dubai–Al-Ain Road to Al Faqa' and Dubai in the north, which also connects to Al Madam in the Emirate of Sharjah via Al-Shwaib.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] It is also connected to Abu Dhabi in the west, Al-Qu'a in the southeast, and Mezyad in the southwest.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Bus and taxi services are available between these areas.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The southern border area of Mezyad lies on the road to Dhank, Ibri and Nizwa in Oman.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The city's airport (Al Ain International Airport) has scheduled passenger flights to Egypt, Pakistan and India.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] A new railway line linking Al-Ain to Abu Dhabi and to the Port of Sohar in Oman is being planned.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al-Ain is developing as a tourist destination.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The dry desert air makes it a welcome retreat from the coastal humidity of the larger cities.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Many Emirati nationals in Abu Dhabi have holiday houses in the city making it a popular weekend destination for families from the capital city.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Its attractions include the Al Ain National Museum, the Al Ain Palace Museum, several restored forts and the Hili Archaeological Park site, dating back to the Bronze Age.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Jebel Hafeet dominates the surrounding area.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] It is popular to visit to the mineral springs at Green Mubazzarah at the base of the mountain, and to drive to the mountaintop at sunset.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Other attractions include Al Ain Zoo, an amusement park named "Hili Fun City", many well-maintained parks popular with families in the summer evenings, and a heritage village.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Opened in 2012, Al Ain Adventure park is located near Jebel Hafeet and provides a range of water-based activities including surfing, kayaking and rafting.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] On top of Jabel Hafeet is the Mercure Hotel.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Mount Hafeet and the nearby 'beehive' tombs are part of what is known as "Jebel Hafeet Desert Park" or "Mezyad Desert Park", which is meant to preserve the nature and geology of the area, besides attracting tourists.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al-Ain has five major malls – Al Ain Mall in the town centre, Al-Jimi Mall in Al-Jimi District, Bawadi Mall in Al-Khrair District, Remal Mall located in the Sanaiya district, and Hili Mall located in the Hili District.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Most commercial activity is centred in and around town centre.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Another popular pastime for Emiratis and expatriates alike is spending time in coffee shops and shisha cafes.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Like the rest of the UAE, Al-Ain has strict laws governing the consumption and distribution of alcohol.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Five facilities in the city currently serve alcohol, four of which are hotels.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] There are many café's in Al-Ain, ranging in size and quality.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The city also has an International standard go-kart circuit.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The city has two English-language radio stations – 100.1 Star FM, which plays English-speaking hits alternating with Arabic-speaking hits, and 105.2 Abu Dhabi Classic FM, which plays classical music, and Arabic Radio Station, which is Abu Dhabi FM 94.9.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] In 2024 the city broke three Guinness World Records.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Once in January as an 8 minute firework and drone display took place, breaking the record for 'Longest straight-line drones display’.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The second took place on the country's 53rd National Day celebrations, as the firework show reached a distance of 11.1 km.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al-Ain is a cultural retreat for residents of the cities of Dubai and Abu Dhabi.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] It is home to a major festival of classical music, and is the home of Al Ain Football Club, which is one of the most successful football clubs in the UAE and Asia.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] It has many titles and championships to its name.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al-Ain Club contains also eight other games which are: handball, volleyball, basketball, swimming, Table Tennis, Athletics, Jiu jitsu, and Taekwondo.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The Al Ain Amblers are a well known rugby club with a long history fielding men's, women's and junior rugby teams in the UAE and Gulf competitions, based at the Al Ain Club.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Al Ain Raceway is one of the region's largest international kart circuits.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Opening in 2007, it hosted the Rotax MAX Grand Finals the same year, and again in 2011.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Hili Fun City hosts two ice hockey teams, the Al Ain Vipers and Ghantoot.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Each team has adult and youth teams starting from age 4.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The Al-Ain Vipers Men's Team won the Emirates Hockey League in the 2009–10 season.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] The Palm Resort to the west of the town hosts a popular rugby club with adult and youth teams, and the Al-Ain International Soccer Club which has three youth teams, including one for 7-9-year-old's.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] There is a water sports centre called "Al Ain Adventure", with a wave pool and surf instructors.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/al-ain] Additionally, the park has facilities for kayaking and rafting on an artificial river.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx (*Oryx leucoryx*), also called the white oryx, was extinct in the wild as of 1972, but was reintroduced to the wild starting in 1982.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The initial reintroduction was primarily from two herds: the "World Herd" originally started at the Phoenix Zoo in 1963 from only nine oryx and the Saudi Arabian herd started in 1986 from private collections and some "World Herd" stock by the Saudi National Wildlife Research Center (NWRC).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009, there have been reintroductions in Oman, Saudi Arabia, Israel, the United Arab Emirates, and Jordan, and as of 2013 the IUCN Red List classifies the species as vulnerable.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx was known to be in decline since the early 1900s in the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] By the 1930, there were two separate populations isolated from each other.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Talbot reported that Arabian oryx appeared to be extinct in its former range along the southern edge of Ar-Rub' al-Khali.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] He believed that any oryx still existing would be exterminated within the next few years and recommended that a captive breeding program be started to save the species.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Michael Crouch, then Assistant Adviser in the Eastern Aden Protectorate, drew attention to the fact that each spring, small groups of oryx still emerged onto the gravel plains in the northeast corner of the Protectorate, where he thought a capture attempt would be possible.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The initial plan of the Fauna and Flora Preservation Society was to establish a herd in Kenya where another species of oryx already lived and flourished.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Kenyan plan was dropped because of an outbreak of hoof-and-mouth disease, and the oryx destined for Kenya were shipped to the Phoenix Zoo instead.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] There were originally four individuals captured and seven donated for this project.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The four were captured in Aden (now Yemen) near the border of Oman by an expedition led by the late Major Ian Grimwood, then chief game warden of Kenya, with help from Manahil and Mahra tribesmen.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] One male from this group later died of capture stress.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The seven donated oryx were: one from the London Zoo, two from Sheikh Jaber Abdullah al-Sabah, and two pairs from the collection of King Saud bin Abdul Aziz.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Five Arabian oryx were delivered to the Phoenix Zoo in 1963 (four in June and one in September).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] A baby was born to the herd in October 1963 from a conception en route and another was born in spring 1964, bringing the starting population of the Phoenix Zoo herd to seven.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The four oryx donated by King Saud arrived at the Phoenix Zoo in July 1964, bringing the population of the "World Herd" to 11.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The breeding program at the Phoenix Zoo was very successful, and the zoo celebrated its 225th Arabian oryx birth in 2002.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] From Phoenix, individuals were sent to other zoos and parks (including the San Diego Wild Animal Park) to start their herds.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Most of the Arabian oryx in the wild today have ancestors from the Phoenix Zoo.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Reintroductions started in 1982 in Oman.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009 there have been reintroductions in Oman, Saudi Arabia, Israel, the United Arab Emirates, and Jordan.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] At this time, populations in the United Arab Emirates and Jordan are still not considered in the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) Red List wild oryx count.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The population in Oman is still receiving supplementary forage, and the introduction into Jordan was after the last update of the Red List.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] By 1980, the number of Arabian oryx in captivity had increased to the point that reintroduction to Oman was attempted from the San Diego Wild Animal Park to Jaaluni in the Jiddat al-Harasis.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The oryx were initially kept in large pens outdoors, but were released to the wild on January 31, 1982, in the Omani Central Desert and Coastal Hills.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] These oryx became the core of the Oman herd in the wild, though there were several other releases of captive bred animals over the next two decades.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The area of their release became the Arabian Oryx Sanctuary.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] On June 28, 2007, Oman's Arabian Oryx Sanctuary was the first site to be removed from the UNESCO World Heritage List.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] UNESCO cited the Omani government's decision to open 90% of the site to oil prospecting as the main reason for this decision.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx population on the site has been reduced from 450 oryx in 1996 to only 65 in 2007, mostly due to poaching and illegal live capture.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] There are now fewer than four breeding pairs left on the site.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Organized captive breeding of the Arabian oryx in Saudi Arabia began in April 1986, when 57 oryx from the farm of the late King Khalid bin Abdul Aziz in King Khalid Wildlife Research Center were brought to the National Wildlife Research Center (NWRC) near At-Ta'if.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Between the initial 1986 founding and 1996, 33 additional oryx (including some from the "World Herd") have been introduced to the founder generation of Arabian oryx at the NWRC.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Since 1996, all additions to the population have been through births.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Due to an outbreak of *Mycobacterium bovis* (bovine tuberculosis) in the founder generation, a "buffer generation" was introduced in the herd.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Since then, calves produced by the founder herd are removed from their dam immediately after birth and hand-reared.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] These hand-reared second generation oryx are regularly tested for tuberculosis and a variety of other pathogenic agents, and join the breeding nucleus only when tests are consecutively negative.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] After breeding, they produce the third generation of oryx, which are tuberculosis free and mother-reared, and of which more than 80% are reintroduced into the wild.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Reintroduction of a wild population began in 1995 in the 'Uruq Bani Ma'arid Protected Area.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The reserve covers about 12,000 km2 (4,600 sq mi) at the western edge of the Rubʿ al-Khali desert or "Empty Quarter".
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009, the IUCN Red List estimates the oryx population on this reserve at 160 individuals.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] A free ranging herd was established in the newly created Mahazat as-Sayd Protected Area in 1989.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] This 2,244 km2 (866 sq mi) fenced reserve is home to reintroduced oryx, gazelle and the houbara bustard.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009, the IUCN Red List estimates the oryx population on this reserve at about 800 individuals.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In Israel the reintroduction program was established in 1978 when four pairs of Arabian oryx were purchased.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] At this time the IUCN Redbook reported wild populations totaling 90–100 animals in three locations in Northern Arava and the Negev Desert.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2014 there are around 130 animals in the Aravah, and in 2013 they began to spread to the central Negev and the population keeps increasing.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In addition to the natural population increase, every year around six animals are released to the wild in Israel.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Israel is the only country in which the Arabian oryx was reintroduced where poaching prohibition can be enforced, and because of this the Israeli population grows annually.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Apart from the wild oryx population in Israel, there are a few dozen oryx in the Yotvata Hai-Bar Nature Reserve, a few breeding couples in the Jerusalem Biblical Zoo and a small herd in the Ramat Gan Safari.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The reintroduction of oryx in Israel is one of a few successful programs reintroducing animals into nature in Israel; others include the introduction of the Persian onager (a proxy for the extinct Syrian onager), and the very successful reintroduction of Persian fallow deer.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In the early 1960s, the late Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan directed the capture of two breeding pairs of the oryx for the nucleus of a captive-breeding program in Al Ain, which would lead to the formation of the city's zoo.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 2007 the United Arab Emirates started releasing animals into Umm Al Zumul.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2009 there have been about 100 animals released.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As part of this initiative, a similar program is being developed to reintroduce this extinct species into its natural habitats in Yemen and Iraq.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Since March 1999, the Emirate of Abu Dhabi has been host to an inter-governmental body known as The Coordinating Committee for the Conservation of the Arabian Oryx, which oversees the coordination of conservation efforts for this species within the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 2012, GSCAO carried out an Arabian Oryx Disease Survey which was funded by the Environment Agency – Abu Dhabi (EAD), in the range states.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx are periodically released in protected areas, such as the Qasr Al Sarab Protected Area.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] As of 2017, it is estimated that around 10,000 Arabian oryx, of which 5,000 are estimated to be in Abu Dhabi, are currently in the United Arab Emirates.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The reintroduction project for Jordan began when the Environment Agency of Abu Dhabi (EAD) and the Al Aqaba Special Economic Zone Authority signed a sponsorship agreement in April 2007.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Under this agreement, EAD is sponsoring the million three-year project which includes reintroduction of the Arabian oryx into the Wadi Rum Protected Area, rehabilitating the habitat, and helping local residents to improve their living standards.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Twenty oryx (12 males and 8 females) were released into the Wadi Rum Protected Area in July 2009.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 1986, as a result of the reintroduction efforts, the IUCN re-listed the Arabian oryx from extinct in the wild to endangered.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] By 2009, the Arabian oryx was protected by law in all areas where it appears.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In June 2011, the Arabian oryx was re-listed as vulnerable by the IUCN Red List.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] In 2016 the IUCN estimated there were more than 1000 Arabian oryx in the wild, with 6000–7000 held in captivity worldwide in zoos, preserves, and private collections.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] Some of these are in large fenced enclosures (free-roaming), including those in Syria (Al Talila), Bahrain, Qatar, and UAE.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] This is the first time the IUCN has re-classified a species as vulnerable after it had been listed as extinct in the wild.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/arabian-oryx-reintroduction] The Arabian oryx is also listed in CITES Appendix I.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] 'Uruq Bani Ma'arid is in an area in which the Arabian oryx used to live before it became extinct in the wild.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] The reserve has been chosen for the reintroduction of oryx that have been bred in a captive breeding programme.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] It has also been selected as being suitable for the re-establishment of herds of Arabian sand gazelle (*Gazella subgutturosa marica*), mountain gazelle (*Gazella gazella*) and ostrich (*Struthio camelus*), all of which have historically inhabited the area.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] The site of this protected area extends from a latitude of 19°30'N and longitude of 45°30'E, to a latitude of 19° 10'N and longitude of 45° 15'E, with a total area of 12,658 km2 (4,887 mi2).
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] As well as the dissected limestone plateau underlying the linear dunes, the reserve includes part of the Tuwaiq Escarpment, wadis and gravel plains.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] The ergs of red sand lie parallel to each other and may be as much as 150 m (492 ft) high.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] They are separated by corridors with sandy or gravelly bases.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] Rainfall is very infrequent and averages about 30 mm (1.2 in) per year.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] Downpours on the escarpment cause the wadis to flow and water drains into the substrate where it is retained.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] 'Uruq Bani Ma'arid has been designated an Important Plant Area because of the richness of its plant life as compared to other parts of the Empty Quarter, and the presence of many plant species endemic to the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] The limestone escarpment has little vegetation but the wadis crease the sides of the escarpment and support a variety of shrubby growth including *Acacias*, grasses and perennial legumes.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] Some scanty vegetation grows on the dunes, particularly *Calligonum crinitum ssp. arabicum* together with sedges and perennial grasses.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] In the corridors between the dunes grow dwarf *Haloxylon persicum*, *Moringa peregrina* and *Commiphora myrrha*.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] Few annual plants grow here, but after rain has fallen there is growth of new shoots on the perennial plants.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] 106 species of plant have been recorded in the reserve.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] Between 1995 and 2013, some 149 Arabian oryx had been released into the reserve, and it was estimated in 2013 that about 500 individuals were present.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] The reserve is unfenced, so this is currently the only population in the wild.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] Arabian sand gazelle and mountain gazelle have also been successfully reintroduced since 1995.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] Other animals that may be seen in the reserve include the Rüppell's fox, sand cat, red fox, Cape hare, desert hedgehog, Cheesman's gerbil, lesser Egyptian jerboa, desert monitor, other lizards and snakes, and feral dogs.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] 104 species of bird have been recorded in the reserve but there are only about 16 resident species.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] Houbara bustard are sometimes seen here, possibly on migration, but the lappet-faced vulture and short-toed snake eagle breed here.
[src:arabian-oryx-reintroduction/uruq-bani-ma-arid] On 20 September 2023, the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia successfully inscribed the 'Uruq Bani Ma'arid Protected Area on the UNESCO World Heritage List as the first-ever Natural World Heritage site in Saudi Arabia.
